  "answer": "**I could not find any passage in the Falsafa corpus's *Diwan-e-Ghalib* where Mirza Ghalib describes the unfaithful (or faithless/infidel) beloved as having no equal in the world.** \n\nThe corpus includes the complete *Diwan-e-Ghalib* ([Mirza Ghalib's collection of 239 ghazals](https://falsafa.com/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/)), with English translations available. Extensive searches across English translations for phrases and concepts like \"unfaithful beloved,\" \"faithless beloved,\" \"no equal,\" \"no rival,\" \"peerless/matchless beloved,\" \"infidel beloved,\" \"beloved equal,\" and combinations with \"Ghalib\" or \"in the world\" returned zero relevant results from this work.[^1]\n\nGhalib frequently writes of the beloved's cruelty (*jafa* or *bewafai*), beauty, and indifference (e.g., in ghazals lamenting unrequited love), but no verse matches this specific description. If it's from another collection, a different translation, or Persian works by Ghalib (not in this Urdu *Diwan*), it's not covered here. The corpus focuses on translated philosophical/classical texts and has only this Ghalib entry.\n\n[^1]: Searches conducted: `\"unfaithful beloved\"`, `faithless beloved`, `\"no equal\" beloved`, `\"no rival\" beloved`, `\"matchless\" beloved`, `\"peerless\" beloved`, `beloved equal`, `\"beloved\" rival`, `\"beauty\" rival`, `\"beauty\" \"no equal\"`, `infidel beloved`, `\"kafir\" beloved`, `\"ghalib\" beloved`, `ghalib \"no equal\"`, `ghalib rival`, `ghalib \"in the world\"`, `beloved` (top 10, none from Ghalib). All on English translation bodies.",
